rick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a medieval given name this is a Norman form of the French name <i>Thierry</i>, from Germanic <i>Theodoric</i>, from <i>þeud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In modern English use it seems at first to have been a transferred use of the surname derived from the medieval given name, and later to have been taken as a pet form of   Terence ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lynn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin: possibly an altered short form of   Linda  , or a derivative of the French name <i>Line</i>, which originated as a short form of various girls' names ending in this syllable, for example <i>Caroline</i>. The element <i>-lyn(n)</i> has been a productive suffix of English girls' names since at least the middle of the 20th century, <i>Lynn</i> itself having enjoyed considerable popularity in the 1950s and 60s, especially."],"variants":[{"name":"Lynne","meanings":["Of uncertain origin: possibly an altered short form of   Linda  , or a derivative of the French name <i>Line</i>, which originated as a short form of various girls' names ending in this syllable, for example <i>Caroline</i>. The element <i>-lyn(n)</i> has been a productive suffix of English girls' names since at least the middle of the 20th century, <i>Lynn</i> itself having enjoyed considerable popularity in the 1950s and 60s, especially."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":